Note:
==============================================================================
rgb - sRGB and Linear-RGB Color Models
==============================================================================

ColorRgb is the canonical floating-point RGB+alpha colour type used by the
T1-6 colour subsystem. Each channel is a Float64 in [0.0, 1.0] holding a
non-linear sRGB-encoded value at the public API boundary. Conversions to
and from linear-light RGB use the piecewise transfer function defined by
IEC 61966-2-1:1999 (the sRGB standard), reproduced here:

    linear = ((srgb + 0.055) / 1.055)^2.4    when srgb >  0.04045
    linear =  srgb / 12.92                   when srgb <= 0.04045
    srgb   = 1.055 * linear^(1/2.4) - 0.055  when linear > 0.0031308
    srgb   = 12.92 * linear                  when linear <= 0.0031308

Hex string parsing accepts the four CSS Color Module Level 4 forms:
    #RGB        (3-digit short)
    #RGBA       (4-digit short with alpha)
    #RRGGBB     (6-digit)
    #RRGGBBAA   (8-digit with alpha)

Alpha compositing follows the Porter-Duff "over" operator (T. Porter and
T. Duff, "Compositing digital images", SIGGRAPH 1984, ACM Computer
Graphics 18(3), pp. 253-259). Public ColorRgb values are NON-premultiplied;
rgb_blend, rgb_premultiply and rgb_unpremultiply manage the
premultiplication on demand. Linear-space interpolation (rgb_lerp_linear)
is the perceptually correct way to mix two sRGB colours.

References:
  - IEC 61966-2-1:1999 (sRGB)
  - W3C CSS Color Module Level 4
  - Porter & Duff, "Compositing Digital Images", SIGGRAPH 1984
==============================================================================
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa" as Arith

Note: ============================================================================
Note: STRUCT TYPE DEFINITION
Note: ============================================================================

Type called "ColorRgb":
    r as Float
    g as Float
    b as Float
    a as Float
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LOCAL HELPERS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "clamp01" takes v as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Saturate a channel into the unit interval [0.0, 1.0]. Boundary guard
    for every ColorRgb constructor.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Two compares against literal endpoints.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two ucomisd + two cmovs.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure function.
    @End Security_Scope
    If v is less than 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    End If
    If v is greater than 1.0:
        Return 1.0
    End If
    Return v
End Process

Process called "absf" takes v as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Floating-point absolute value used by sRGB transfer below the
    threshold branch.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Single compare; negate when negative.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One ucomisd + one negate.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If v is less than 0.0:
        Return 0.0 minus v
    End If
    Return v
End Process

Process called "powf_real" takes base as Float, exponent as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Real-valued exponentiation x^y for x > 0 implemented via
    exp(y * ln(x)). The Taylor / Pade-style series here are normalised so
    that all intermediate computations stay in the convergence region.
    Required by the sRGB transfer functions which use exponents 2.4 and
    1/2.4 = 0.41666... Both ln and exp are seeded from range-reductions
    that keep the residual in [-0.5, 0.5] for ln and [0, ln 2] for exp.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Range-reduces x via the bit-pattern exponent split (here approximated
    by halving / doubling loops since we do not have direct exponent
    extraction), then evaluates ln(m) for m in [1, 2) via a 20-term
    Mercator series. Multiplies by the exponent to get y*ln(x), then
    evaluates exp via a 25-term Maclaurin expansion. Returns 0.0 for
    base <= 0 (sRGB transfer never invokes powf_real on a negative value
    because sign is stripped beforehand).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    ~ 45 multiplies + 25 multiplies = O(70 FLOPs) per call. Adequate for
    transfer-curve evaluation; not intended as a hot path.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure. Bounded iteration counts guarantee termination.
    @End Security_Scope
    If base is less than or equal to 0.0:
        Return 0.0
    End If
    Let m be base
    Let k be 0
    While m is greater than or equal to 2.0:
        Set m to m divided by 2.0
        Set k to k plus 1
        If k is greater than 2048:
            Return 0.0
        End If
    End While
    Let k_dn be 0
    While m is less than 1.0:
        Set m to m multiplied by 2.0
        Set k_dn to k_dn plus 1
        If k_dn is greater than 2048:
            Return 0.0
        End If
    End While
    Let z be (m minus 1.0) divided by (m plus 1.0)
    Let z2 be z multiplied by z
    Let term be z
    Let ln_m be 0.0
    Let idx be 0
    While idx is less than 30:
        Let denom be Arith.int_to_float((2 multiplied by idx) plus 1)
        Set ln_m to ln_m plus (term divided by denom)
        Set term to term multiplied by z2
        Set idx to idx plus 1
    End While
    Set ln_m to ln_m multiplied by 2.0
    Let ln2 be 0.69314718055994530941723212145817656807550013436025525412
    Let ln_base be ln_m plus (Arith.int_to_float(k) multiplied by ln2)
    Set ln_base to ln_base minus (Arith.int_to_float(k_dn) multiplied by ln2)
    Let y be exponent multiplied by ln_base
    Let n_floor be Arith.float_to_int(y divided by ln2)
    If y is less than 0.0:
        If Arith.int_to_float(n_floor) is greater than (y divided by ln2):
            Set n_floor to n_floor minus 1
        End If
    End If
    Let r_y be y minus (Arith.int_to_float(n_floor) multiplied by ln2)
    Let exp_r be 1.0
    Let s_term be 1.0
    Let i be 1
    While i is less than 32:
        Set s_term to (s_term multiplied by r_y) divided by Arith.int_to_float(i)
        Set exp_r to exp_r plus s_term
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Let two_n be 1.0
    If n_floor is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let nn be n_floor
        While nn is greater than 0:
            Set two_n to two_n multiplied by 2.0
            Set nn to nn minus 1
        End While
    Otherwise:
        Let nn be 0 minus n_floor
        While nn is greater than 0:
            Set two_n to two_n divided by 2.0
            Set nn to nn minus 1
        End While
    End If
    Return exp_r multiplied by two_n
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONSTRUCTORS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "rgb_create" takes r as Float, g as Float, b as Float, a as Float returns ColorRgb:
    @Reasoning
    Construct a ColorRgb from four Float channel values in [0, 1], clamping
    out-of-range inputs to the unit interval.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Per-component clamp via clamp01 before assignment.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four clamps plus one struct allocation.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure transformation.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let c be a value of type ColorRgb
    Set c.r to clamp01(r)
    Set c.g to clamp01(g)
    Set c.b to clamp01(b)
    Set c.a to clamp01(a)
    Return c
End Process

Process called "rgb_from_u8" takes r as Integer, g as Integer, b as Integer, a as Integer returns ColorRgb:
    @Reasoning
    Build a ColorRgb from four uint8 channel values in [0, 255]. Channels
    outside [0, 255] saturate to that range before dividing by 255.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Clamp each channel to [0, 255] then scale by 1/255.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four integer clamps, four divides.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let rr be r
    Let gg be g
    Let bb be b
    Let aa be a
    If rr is less than 0:
        Set rr to 0
    End If
    If rr is greater than 255:
        Set rr to 255
    End If
    If gg is less than 0:
        Set gg to 0
    End If
    If gg is greater than 255:
        Set gg to 255
    End If
    If bb is less than 0:
        Set bb to 0
    End If
    If bb is greater than 255:
        Set bb to 255
    End If
    If aa is less than 0:
        Set aa to 0
    End If
    If aa is greater than 255:
        Set aa to 255
    End If
    Let c be a value of type ColorRgb
    Set c.r to Arith.int_to_float(rr) divided by 255.0
    Set c.g to Arith.int_to_float(gg) divided by 255.0
    Set c.b to Arith.int_to_float(bb) divided by 255.0
    Set c.a to Arith.int_to_float(aa) divided by 255.0
    Return c
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: CONVERSIONS TO PACKED FORMATS
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "channel_to_u8" takes v as Float returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Quantise a unit-interval Float channel to its 8-bit representation,
    using round-half-to-even consistent with floor(x*255 + 0.5).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Multiply by 255, add 0.5, truncate, then clamp.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two FP ops plus a convert-to-int.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let clamped be clamp01(v)
    Let scaled be (clamped multiplied by 255.0) plus 0.5
    Let i be Arith.float_to_int(scaled)
    If i is less than 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If i is greater than 255:
        Return 255
    End If
    Return i
End Process

Process called "rgb_to_u8" takes c as ColorRgb, out_buf as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Quantise the four channels into the caller-supplied 4-byte buffer in
    R,G,B,A order. Buffer ownership is the caller's.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Four channel_to_u8 calls plus four byte stores.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four FP-to-int conversions, four stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller guarantees out_buf has at least 4 writable bytes.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let _r be Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buf, 0, channel_to_u8(c.r))
    Let _g be Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buf, 1, channel_to_u8(c.g))
    Let _b be Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buf, 2, channel_to_u8(c.b))
    Let _a be Memory.memory_set_byte(out_buf, 3, channel_to_u8(c.a))
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "rgb_to_u32_argb" takes c as ColorRgb returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Pack the colour into a 32-bit ARGB word with alpha in the high byte
    (0xAARRGGBB). Layout used by Win32 / DirectX / Cairo / NSColor.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Channel quantisation followed by integer shifts and ors. The shift
    counts are weaker than +/- so each shift is parenthesised.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four converts + three shifts + three ors.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let r8 be channel_to_u8(c.r)
    Let g8 be channel_to_u8(c.g)
    Let b8 be channel_to_u8(c.b)
    Let a8 be channel_to_u8(c.a)
    Let result be (a8 shifted left by 24) bit_or (r8 shifted left by 16)
    Set result to result bit_or (g8 shifted left by 8)
    Set result to result bit_or b8
    Return result
End Process

Process called "rgb_to_u32_rgba" takes c as ColorRgb returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Pack the colour into a 32-bit RGBA word with alpha in the low byte
    (0xRRGGBBAA). Layout used by OpenGL textures and PNG image rows.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Channel quantisation followed by integer shifts and ors with the
    shift counts parenthesised since shift is weaker than +/-.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Four converts + three shifts + three ors.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let r8 be channel_to_u8(c.r)
    Let g8 be channel_to_u8(c.g)
    Let b8 be channel_to_u8(c.b)
    Let a8 be channel_to_u8(c.a)
    Let result be (r8 shifted left by 24) bit_or (g8 shifted left by 16)
    Set result to result bit_or (b8 shifted left by 8)
    Set result to result bit_or a8
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HEX STRING ENCODING / DECODING
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "hex_digit_byte" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Map a nibble value 0..15 to its ASCII lowercase hex digit byte.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    [0..9] -> '0'..'9' (48..57); [10..15] -> 'a'..'f' (97..102).
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two compares, two arithmetic ops.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If value is less than 0:
        Return 48
    End If
    If value is less than 10:
        Return value plus 48
    End If
    If value is less than 16:
        Return (value minus 10) plus 97
    End If
    Return 48
End Process

Process called "hex_value_of_byte" takes ch as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse of hex_digit_byte. Maps ASCII hex digit to 0..15; returns -1
    on non-hex input.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Three ranges: '0'..'9', 'a'..'f', 'A'..'F'.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Six compares maximum.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    If ch is greater than or equal to 48:
        If ch is less than or equal to 57:
            Return ch minus 48
        End If
    End If
    If ch is greater than or equal to 97:
        If ch is less than or equal to 102:
            Return (ch minus 97) plus 10
        End If
    End If
    If ch is greater than or equal to 65:
        If ch is less than or equal to 70:
            Return (ch minus 65) plus 10
        End If
    End If
    Return 0 minus 1
End Process

Process called "write_hex_byte_into" takes buf as Integer, offset as Integer, byte_val as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Emit a two-character lowercase hex encoding of an 8-bit value into
    buf at offset; returns the next offset.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    High nibble then low nibble.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Two stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller owns buf.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let v be byte_val
    If v is less than 0:
        Set v to 0
    End If
    If v is greater than 255:
        Set v to 255
    End If
    Let hi be v divided by 16
    Let lo be v modulo by 16
    Let _h be Memory.memory_set_byte(buf, offset, hex_digit_byte(hi))
    Let _l be Memory.memory_set_byte(buf, offset plus 1, hex_digit_byte(lo))
    Return offset plus 2
End Process

Process called "rgb_to_hex_string" takes c as ColorRgb, include_alpha as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Serialise to "#rrggbb" when include_alpha is 0, or "#rrggbbaa" when
    include_alpha is non-zero. Returns a heap-allocated NUL-terminated
    byte buffer.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Allocates 8 or 10 bytes, writes '#', then channel pairs.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single allocation, fixed-size write sequence.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Caller must Layout.deallocate the returned pointer.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let alpha_form be 0
    If include_alpha is not equal to 0:
        Set alpha_form to 1
    End If
    Let needed be 8
    If alpha_form is equal to 1:
        Set needed to 10
    End If
    Let buf be Layout.allocate(needed)
    If buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let _h be Memory.memory_set_byte(buf, 0, 35)
    Let off be write_hex_byte_into(buf, 1, channel_to_u8(c.r))
    Set off to write_hex_byte_into(buf, off, channel_to_u8(c.g))
    Set off to write_hex_byte_into(buf, off, channel_to_u8(c.b))
    If alpha_form is equal to 1:
        Set off to write_hex_byte_into(buf, off, channel_to_u8(c.a))
        Let _z be Memory.memory_set_byte(buf, 9, 0)
    Otherwise:
        Let _z be Memory.memory_set_byte(buf, 7, 0)
    End If
    Return buf
End Process

Process called "rgb_from_hex_string" takes s as Integer returns ColorRgb:
    @Reasoning
    Parse a CSS Color Module Level 4 hex notation into a ColorRgb. Accepts
    3, 4, 6, or 8 hex digits with an optional leading '#'. Invalid input
    yields opaque black.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Length-dispatch: 3-digit -> double each nibble; 4-digit -> +alpha;
    6-digit -> pairwise; 8-digit -> +alpha pairwise.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Bounded loop reading at most 9 input characters.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Validates each character via hex_value_of_byte and rejects invalid
    forms without crashing.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type ColorRgb
    Set out.r to 0.0
    Set out.g to 0.0
    Set out.b to 0.0
    Set out.a to 1.0
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return out
    End If
    Let total_len be 0
    Let scan be 0
    While scan is less than 256:
        Let ch be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, scan)
        If ch is equal to 0:
            Set scan to 256
        Otherwise:
            Set total_len to total_len plus 1
            Set scan to scan plus 1
        End If
    End While
    Let start be 0
    If total_len is greater than 0:
        Let first be Memory.memory_get_byte(s, 0)
        If first is equal to 35:
            Set start to 1
        End If
    End If
    Let hex_len be total_len minus start
    If hex_len is equal to 3:
        Let r_n be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start))
        Let g_n be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start plus 1))
        Let b_n be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start plus 2))
        If r_n is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        If g_n is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        If b_n is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        Set out.r to Arith.int_to_float((r_n multiplied by 16) plus r_n) divided by 255.0
        Set out.g to Arith.int_to_float((g_n multiplied by 16) plus g_n) divided by 255.0
        Set out.b to Arith.int_to_float((b_n multiplied by 16) plus b_n) divided by 255.0
        Set out.a to 1.0
        Return out
    End If
    If hex_len is equal to 4:
        Let r_n be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start))
        Let g_n be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start plus 1))
        Let b_n be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start plus 2))
        Let a_n be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start plus 3))
        If r_n is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        If g_n is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        If b_n is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        If a_n is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        Set out.r to Arith.int_to_float((r_n multiplied by 16) plus r_n) divided by 255.0
        Set out.g to Arith.int_to_float((g_n multiplied by 16) plus g_n) divided by 255.0
        Set out.b to Arith.int_to_float((b_n multiplied by 16) plus b_n) divided by 255.0
        Set out.a to Arith.int_to_float((a_n multiplied by 16) plus a_n) divided by 255.0
        Return out
    End If
    If hex_len is equal to 6:
        Let r_hi be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start))
        Let r_lo be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start plus 1))
        Let g_hi be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start plus 2))
        Let g_lo be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start plus 3))
        Let b_hi be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start plus 4))
        Let b_lo be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start plus 5))
        If r_hi is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        If r_lo is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        If g_hi is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        If g_lo is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        If b_hi is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        If b_lo is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        Set out.r to Arith.int_to_float((r_hi multiplied by 16) plus r_lo) divided by 255.0
        Set out.g to Arith.int_to_float((g_hi multiplied by 16) plus g_lo) divided by 255.0
        Set out.b to Arith.int_to_float((b_hi multiplied by 16) plus b_lo) divided by 255.0
        Set out.a to 1.0
        Return out
    End If
    If hex_len is equal to 8:
        Let r_hi be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start))
        Let r_lo be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start plus 1))
        Let g_hi be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start plus 2))
        Let g_lo be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start plus 3))
        Let b_hi be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start plus 4))
        Let b_lo be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start plus 5))
        Let a_hi be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start plus 6))
        Let a_lo be hex_value_of_byte(Memory.memory_get_byte(s, start plus 7))
        If r_hi is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        If r_lo is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        If g_hi is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        If g_lo is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        If b_hi is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        If b_lo is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        If a_hi is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        If a_lo is less than 0:
            Return out
        End If
        Set out.r to Arith.int_to_float((r_hi multiplied by 16) plus r_lo) divided by 255.0
        Set out.g to Arith.int_to_float((g_hi multiplied by 16) plus g_lo) divided by 255.0
        Set out.b to Arith.int_to_float((b_hi multiplied by 16) plus b_lo) divided by 255.0
        Set out.a to Arith.int_to_float((a_hi multiplied by 16) plus a_lo) divided by 255.0
        Return out
    End If
    Return out
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: sRGB <-> LINEAR TRANSFER FUNCTIONS (IEC 61966-2-1)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "srgb_to_linear" takes c as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Map a sRGB-encoded scalar in [0, 1] to its linear-light equivalent
    using the piecewise definition from IEC 61966-2-1:1999. The toe
    region (srgb <= 0.04045) is linear with slope 1/12.92; above the toe
    the transform is ((srgb + 0.055) / 1.055)^2.4. Negative inputs are
    handled with sign-preservation so that the function is well-defined
    as an odd extension.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Strip the sign, dispatch on the 0.04045 threshold, evaluate the
    appropriate branch with powf_real(., 2.4) for the gamma branch, and
    reapply the sign.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Toe branch is two FP ops; gamma branch dominated by powf_real
    (~70 FLOPs).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure. Defined for all finite real inputs.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let sign be 1.0
    Let a be c
    If c is less than 0.0:
        Set sign to 0.0 minus 1.0
        Set a to 0.0 minus c
    End If
    Let result be 0.0
    If a is less than or equal to 0.04045:
        Set result to a divided by 12.92
    Otherwise:
        Let inside be (a plus 0.055) divided by 1.055
        Set result to powf_real(inside, 2.4)
    End If
    Return sign multiplied by result
End Process

Process called "linear_to_srgb" takes c as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Inverse of srgb_to_linear. Linear toe (slope 12.92) for linear values
    <= 0.0031308 transitions smoothly into 1.055*linear^(1/2.4) - 0.055
    above the toe.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Sign-preserving dispatch. Calls powf_real(., 1.0 / 2.4) on the
    gamma branch.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Same cost profile as srgb_to_linear.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let sign be 1.0
    Let a be c
    If c is less than 0.0:
        Set sign to 0.0 minus 1.0
        Set a to 0.0 minus c
    End If
    Let result be 0.0
    If a is less than or equal to 0.0031308:
        Set result to a multiplied by 12.92
    Otherwise:
        Let inv_gamma be 1.0 divided by 2.4
        Set result to (1.055 multiplied by powf_real(a, inv_gamma)) minus 0.055
    End If
    Return sign multiplied by result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: PORTER-DUFF "OVER" BLEND + PREMULTIPLICATION
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "rgb_premultiply" takes c as ColorRgb returns ColorRgb:
    @Reasoning
    Convert a non-premultiplied ColorRgb to premultiplied form by scaling
    each RGB channel by alpha. The alpha channel is preserved.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Per-channel multiply by alpha.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Three multiplies, one struct allocation.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type ColorRgb
    Set out.r to c.r multiplied by c.a
    Set out.g to c.g multiplied by c.a
    Set out.b to c.b multiplied by c.a
    Set out.a to c.a
    Return out
End Process

Process called "rgb_unpremultiply" takes c as ColorRgb returns ColorRgb:
    @Reasoning
    Convert a premultiplied ColorRgb back to non-premultiplied form by
    dividing each RGB channel by alpha. Fully transparent input yields a
    zero RGB output to avoid division by zero.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Guards alpha = 0; otherwise reciprocal-multiply.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    One reciprocal + three multiplies.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let out be a value of type ColorRgb
    If c.a is less than or equal to 0.0:
        Set out.r to 0.0
        Set out.g to 0.0
        Set out.b to 0.0
        Set out.a to 0.0
        Return out
    End If
    Let inv_a be 1.0 divided by c.a
    Set out.r to c.r multiplied by inv_a
    Set out.g to c.g multiplied by inv_a
    Set out.b to c.b multiplied by inv_a
    Set out.a to c.a
    Return out
End Process

Process called "rgb_blend" takes top as ColorRgb, base as ColorRgb, alpha as Float returns ColorRgb:
    @Reasoning
    Porter-Duff "over" composite of the top layer (already scaled by the
    explicit alpha argument and its own alpha) onto the base layer. The
    formula in straight-alpha form is:

        a_out = a_top*alpha + a_base*(1 - a_top*alpha)
        c_out = (c_top*(a_top*alpha) + c_base*a_base*(1 - a_top*alpha)) / a_out

    Special-cased when a_out is zero (returns transparent black).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Combines top.a with the explicit alpha multiplier, then performs the
    canonical Porter-Duff calculation in straight-alpha space.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Approximately ten FP ops per call.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let mix_a be top.a multiplied by clamp01(alpha)
    Let one_minus_mix be 1.0 minus mix_a
    Let out_a be mix_a plus (base.a multiplied by one_minus_mix)
    Let result be a value of type ColorRgb
    If out_a is less than or equal to 0.0:
        Set result.r to 0.0
        Set result.g to 0.0
        Set result.b to 0.0
        Set result.a to 0.0
        Return result
    End If
    Let num_r be (top.r multiplied by mix_a) plus ((base.r multiplied by base.a) multiplied by one_minus_mix)
    Let num_g be (top.g multiplied by mix_a) plus ((base.g multiplied by base.a) multiplied by one_minus_mix)
    Let num_b be (top.b multiplied by mix_a) plus ((base.b multiplied by base.a) multiplied by one_minus_mix)
    Set result.r to num_r divided by out_a
    Set result.g to num_g divided by out_a
    Set result.b to num_b divided by out_a
    Set result.a to out_a
    Return result
End Process

Process called "rgb_lerp_linear" takes c1 as ColorRgb, c2 as ColorRgb, t as Float returns ColorRgb:
    @Reasoning
    Linearly interpolate between two sRGB-encoded colours in LINEAR light
    space, then re-encode the result back to sRGB. This is the
    perceptually correct way to blend two sRGB samples and avoids the
    muddy mid-tones that result from naive sRGB-space interpolation.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    1. srgb_to_linear each channel of c1 and c2
    2. lerp each linear channel by t in [0, 1]
    3. linear_to_srgb each interpolated channel
    Alpha is interpolated linearly in straight-alpha space.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Six srgb_to_linear plus three linear_to_srgb evaluations -> the
    powf_real cost dominates.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let tt be clamp01(t)
    Let one_minus_t be 1.0 minus tt
    Let r1_lin be srgb_to_linear(c1.r)
    Let g1_lin be srgb_to_linear(c1.g)
    Let b1_lin be srgb_to_linear(c1.b)
    Let r2_lin be srgb_to_linear(c2.r)
    Let g2_lin be srgb_to_linear(c2.g)
    Let b2_lin be srgb_to_linear(c2.b)
    Let r_mix be (r1_lin multiplied by one_minus_t) plus (r2_lin multiplied by tt)
    Let g_mix be (g1_lin multiplied by one_minus_t) plus (g2_lin multiplied by tt)
    Let b_mix be (b1_lin multiplied by one_minus_t) plus (b2_lin multiplied by tt)
    Let out be a value of type ColorRgb
    Set out.r to linear_to_srgb(r_mix)
    Set out.g to linear_to_srgb(g_mix)
    Set out.b to linear_to_srgb(b_mix)
    Set out.a to (c1.a multiplied by one_minus_t) plus (c2.a multiplied by tt)
    Return out
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: ACCESSORS (provided so other primitives can avoid touching struct fields
Note: across the module boundary which the bootstrap parser does not permit
Note: when the type lives in another module's namespace).
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "rgb_r" takes c as ColorRgb returns Float:
    @Reasoning
    Read the red channel of a ColorRgb. Trivial accessor exposed for
    cross-module callers that cannot dereference qualified struct fields.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
    Direct field read.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
    Single load.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
    Pure.
    @End Security_Scope
    Return c.r
End Process

Process called "rgb_g" takes c as ColorRgb returns Float:
    @Reasoning
